# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: save-game-serialization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] This is a **comparison of data serialization formats**, various ways to convert complex objects to sequences of bits.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] It does not include markup languages used exclusively as document file formats.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The "classic" format is plain text, and an XML format is also supported.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Theoretically possible due to abstraction, but no implementation is included.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but text and JSON formats are available.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**Means that generic tools/libraries know how to encode, decode, and dereference a reference to another piece of data in the same document.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] A tool may require the IDL file, but no more.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Excludes custom, non-standardized referencing techniques.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**ASN.1 has X.681 (Information Object System), X.682 (Constraints), and X.683 (Parameterization) that allow for the precise specification of open types where the types of values can be identified by integers, by OIDs, etc.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] OIDs are a standard format for globally unique identifiers, as well as a standard notation ("absolute reference") for referencing a component of a value.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] For example, PKIX uses such notation in RFC 5912.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] With such notation (constraints on parameterized types using information object sets), generic ASN.1 tools/libraries can automatically encode/decode/resolve references within a document.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, a json encoder is available.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The primary format is binary, but a text format is available.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The RFC CSV specification only deals with delimiters, newlines, and quote characters; it does not directly deal with serializing programming data structures.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**The netstrings specification only deals with nested byte strings; anything else is outside the scope of the specification.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**PHP will unserialize any floating-point number correctly, but will serialize them to their full decimal expansion.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**XML data bindings and SOAP serialization tools provide type-safe XML serialization of programming data structures into XML.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Shown are XML values that can be placed in XML elements and attributes.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] **^**This syntax is not compatible with the Internet-Draft, but is used by some dialects of Lisp.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] All basic Ion types have a null variant, as its 0xXf tag.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Any tag beginning with 0x0X other than 0x0f defines ignored padding.
[src:save-game-serialization/comparison-of-data-serialization-formats] Interpretation of Netstrings is entirely application- or schema-dependent.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] Data structures processed by MessagePack loosely correspond to those used in JSON format.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] MessagePack is more compact than JSON, but imposes limitations on array and integer sizes.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] On the other hand, it allows binary data and non-UTF-8 strings.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] In JSON, map keys have to be strings, but MessagePack has no such limitation, and any type can be a map key, including types like maps and arrays, and, like YAML, numbers.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] Compared to BSON, MessagePack is more space-efficient.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] BSON is designed for fast in-memory manipulation, whereas MessagePack is designed for efficient transmission over the wire.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] For example, BSON requires null terminators at the end of all strings and inserts string indexes for list elements, while MessagePack does not.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] BSON represents both arrays and maps internally as documents, which are maps, where an array is a map with keys as decimal strings counting up from 0.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] MessagePack on the other hand represents both maps and arrays as arrays, where each map key–value pair is contiguous, making odd items keys and even items values.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] The Protocol Buffers format provides a significantly more compact transmission format than MessagePack because it does not transmit field names.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] However, while JSON and MessagePack aim to serialize arbitrary data structures with type tags, Protocol Buffers requires a schema to define the data types.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] Protocol Buffers compiler creates boilerplate code in the target language to facilitate integration of serialization into the application code; MessagePack returns only a dynamically typed data structure and provides no automatic structure checks.
[src:save-game-serialization/messagepack] MessagePack is referenced in RFC 7049 of CBOR.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] In computer science, **persistence** refers to the characteristic of state of a system that outlives (persists for longer than) the process that created it.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] This is achieved in practice by storing the state as data in computer data storage.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Programs have to transfer data to and from storage devices and have to provide mappings from the native programming-language data structures to the storage device data structures.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Picture editing programs or word processors, for example, achieve state persistence by saving their documents to files.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Persistence is said to be "orthogonal" or "transparent" when it is implemented as an intrinsic property of the execution environment of a program.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] An orthogonal persistence environment does not require any specific actions by programs running in it to retrieve or save their state.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Non-orthogonal persistence requires data to be written and read to and from storage using specific instructions in a program, resulting in the use of *persist* as a transitive verb: *On completion, the program persists the data*.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] The advantage of orthogonal persistence environments is simpler and less error-prone programs.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] The term "persistent" was first introduced by Atkinson and Morrison in the sense of orthogonal persistence: they used an adjective rather than a verb to emphasize persistence as a property of the data, as distinct from an imperative action performed by a program.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] The use of the transitive verb "persist" (describing an action performed by a program) is a back-formation.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Orthogonal persistence is widely adopted in operating systems for hibernation and in platform virtualization systems such as VMware and VirtualBox for state saving.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Research prototype languages such as PS-algol, Napier88, Fibonacci and pJama, successfully demonstrated the concepts along with the advantages to programmers.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Using system images is the simplest persistence strategy.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Notebook hibernation is an example of orthogonal persistence using a system image because it does not require any actions by the programs running on the machine.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] An example of non-orthogonal persistence using a system image is a simple text editing program executing specific instructions to save an entire document to a file.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Using journals is the second simplest persistence technique.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Journaling is the process of storing events in a log before each one is applied to a system.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] On startup, the journal is read and each event is reapplied to the system, avoiding data loss in the case of system failure or shutdown.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] The entire "Undo/Redo" history of user commands in a picture editing program, for example, when written to a file, constitutes a journal capable of recovering the state of an edited picture at any point in time.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Journals are used by journaling file systems, prevalent systems and database management systems where they are also called "transaction logs" or "redo logs".
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] This technique is the writing to storage of only those portions of system state that have been modified (are dirty) since their last write.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Sophisticated document editing applications, for example, will use dirty writes to save only those portions of a document that were actually changed since the last save.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Any software layer that makes it easier for a program to persist its state is generically called a persistence layer.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Most persistence layers will not achieve persistence directly but will use an underlying database management system.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] System prevalence is a technique that combines system images and transaction journals, mentioned above, to overcome their limitations.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] DBMSs use a combination of the dirty writes and transaction journaling techniques mentioned above.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] They provide not only persistence but also other services such as queries, auditing and access control.
[src:save-game-serialization/persistence-computer-science] Persistent operating systems are operating systems that remain persistent even after a crash or unexpected shutdown.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:save-game-serialization/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A **saved game** (also called a **game save**, **savegame**, **savefile**, **save point**, or simply **save**) is a piece of digitally stored information about the progress of a player in a video game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] From the earliest games in the 1970s onward, game platform hardware and memory improved, which led to bigger and more complex computer games, which, in turn, tended to take more and more time to play them from start to finish.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] This naturally led to the need to store in some way the progress, and how to handle the case where the player received a "game over".
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] More modern games with a heavier emphasis on storytelling are designed to allow the player many choices that impact the story in a profound way later on, and some game designers do not want to allow more than one save game so that the experience will always be "fresh".
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Game designers allow players to prevent the loss of progress in the game (as might happen after a game over or character death).
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Games designed this way encourage players to 'try things out', and on regretting a choice, continue from an earlier point on.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Although the feature of save games often allows for gameplay to resume after a game over, a notable exception is in games where save games are deleted when it is game over.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Several names are used to describe this feature, including "permadeath", "iron man", and "hardcore", and the feature has developed over the years from being the only kind of save system per game to the more modern 'suspend game' feature among regular save points.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For online games, the game's progress is maintained on the remote server.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In some games, upon resuming the game from a save game, the software locks or marks the save game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Early examples include *Moria* and *Diablo II*'s "hardcore" mode where the character save game is managed by the server.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The use of saved games is very common in modern video games, particularly in role-playing video games, which are usually much too long to finish in a single session.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In early video games, there was no need for saving games, since these games usually had no actual plot to develop and were generally very short in length.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Classic arcade video games from the golden age of arcade video games did not save the player's progress towards completing the game, but rather high scores, custom settings, and other features.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The first game to save the player's score was Taito's seminal 1978 shoot 'em up title *Space Invaders*.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For cartridge-based console games, such as Taito's *Mirai Shinwa Jarvas* (1987), *The Legend of Zelda* (1987) and *Kirby's Adventure* (1993), saved games were stored in battery-backed random-access memory on the game cartridge itself.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] *Pop and Chips* (1985) for the Super Cassette Vision was the first-ever game to allow saving game progress on a video game console, using an AA battery on the game cassette.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In modern consoles, which use disks for storing games, saved games are stored in other ways, such as by use of memory cards or internal hard drives on the game machine itself.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The use of memory cards for saving game data dates back to SNK's cartridge-based Neo Geo arcade system and home console in 1990.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Depending on the game, a player will have the ability to save the game either at any arbitrary point (usually when the game has been paused), after a specific task has been completed (such as at the end of a level), or at designated areas within the game known as save points.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The available ways to save a game affect gameplay, and can represent a practice of players or an explicit decision by designers to give the game a particular feel or alter its difficulty.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A video game may allow the user to save at any point of the game at any time.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] There are also modified versions of this.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For example, in the GameCube game *Eternal Darkness*, the player can save at almost any time, but only if no enemies are in the room.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] To make gaming more engaging, some video games may impose a limit on the number of times a player saves the game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For instance, *IGI 2* allows only a handful of saves in each mission; *Max Payne 2* imposes this restriction on the highest level of difficulty.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some video games only allow the game to be saved at predetermined points in the game, called save points (Not to be confused with "checkpoints").
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Save points are employed either because the game is too complex to allow saving at any given point or to attempt to make the game more challenging by forcing the player to rely on their skills instead of on the ability to retry indefinitely.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Save points are easier to program and thus attractive from a development standpoint.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some games use a hybrid system where both save anywhere and save points are used.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For example, *Final Fantasy VII* permits saving anywhere when the player is traveling on the world map, but once the player enters a location (e.g. town, cavern or forest), saving is only possible at save points.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Overusing saved games may be seen as unfair and in such a context is referred to as "savescumming".
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Savescumming makes losing a game impossible because whenever the player loses or is about to lose, a savegame is loaded, effectively turning back time to the situation before the loss.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In a video game, this could for example be done when the player loses a battle/race, misses the best performance grading for a level (such as an S-rank) or runs into an unwinnable situation by losing anyone or anything needed to continue and win.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For example, in a game that features a casino, the player could save the game and then bet all their in-game money on black at a roulette table.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] If the outcome is black, their money is doubled and the player saves the game again.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] If the outcome is red (or green), the player disregards this outcome by reloading their last savegame.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] This allows for an indefinite winning streak.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Game programmers may defend against savescumming by various means, such as checking timestamps.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For example, on multiuser Unix systems, *NetHack* uses setgid to prevent users from copying save files into the necessary directory.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Another technique is to use a deterministic, seeded pseudorandom number generator, so that undesired random outcomes cannot be avoided simply by saving and reloading.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In this situation, when the player reloads a saved game, "random" events will occur identically every time – the only way to get a different outcome is to play differently.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some video games save the game in progress automatically, such as after the pass of a fixed amount of time, at certain predetermined points in the game as an extension to the save point concept, or when the player exits.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some games only permit "suspend saves" in which the game is automatically saved upon exiting and reloaded upon restarting.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The aim of a suspend save is only to allow the gameplay to be temporarily interrupted; as such, suspend saves are erased when the player resumes the game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] This concept was popularized by *Rogue* and the namesake genre, which are known for employing the mechanic such that if the player were to die in the game, their save file is deleted and the game must be restarted.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The term "perma-death" would come to refer to the concept used for that purpose.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] It is possible to cheat the system by copying and reusing suspend save files in an act of what is considered to be a form of savescumming.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] "Checkpoints" are locations in a video game where a player character respawns after death.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Characters generally respawn at the last checkpoint that they have reached.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A respawn is most often due to the death of the in-game character, but it can also be caused by the failure to meet an objective required to advance in the game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Checkpoints might be temporary, as they stop working when the player loses their last life, completes or quits the level, especially in platform games.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Most modern games, however, save the game to memory at these points, known as auto-saving.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Checkpoints might be visible or invisible to the player.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Visible checkpoints might give a player a sense of security when activated, but in turn sacrifice some immersion, as checkpoints are intrinsically "gamey" and might even need an explanation of how they work unless they are diegetic.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Invisible checkpoints do not break immersion but may make players unsure of where they will respawn, if the heads-up display does not give a visible indication that a checkpoint was reached.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Quick-saving and quick-loading allow the player to save or load the game with a single keystroke.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The term "quick save" may be used in video games that lack the traditional saving mechanism altogether.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The advantage of quick saving is its low burden: The player only has to press a button and, if applicable, wait a few seconds.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The disadvantage is the automatic loss of the previous quick-saved game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Games that only offer quick saving may be impossible to play by two different players (or more) unless there is a mechanism to distinguish players, such as user accounts.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Leaving the decision of when to save up to the player increases the likelihood that a save will be made during a less than favourable game state.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A quicksave shortly before an event which kills the player creates what is known as a death loop.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Passwords are a form of saved game not stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Instead, everything needed to reconstruct the game state is encoded in and displayed on-screen as a string of text, usually comprising random alphanumeric characters, and the player can then record or memorize it.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The player may later resume play from that point by entering the same password.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Passwords were widely used by home console games before the advent of non-volatile memory and later internal and external storage.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A "save state" is a form of a saved game in emulators.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A save state is generated when the emulator stores the contents of random-access memory of an emulated program to disk.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Save states enable players to save their games even when the emulated game or system does not support the feature.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For instance, save states may be used to circumvent saving restrictions or as a savescumming technique.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] An associated concept is **save state hacking**, the practice of which uses a hex editor to modify the save states to alter gameplay conditions, usually in favor of the player.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Save states are comparable to snapshots of a computer system's state or hibernation in computing, with save states being a limited form of snapshots.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Save states have started to receive mainstream usage in the early 2010s with Nintendo's Virtual Console.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some Wii U and 3DS Virtual Console titles allow players to save a "restore point," which is like a quick save but has no restrictions on reloading.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Although likely derived from quick saves, restore points are functionally identical to save states, and can be used for many of the same purposes.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The Switch's "Nintendo Classics" software has a similar feature, referred to as "suspend points", which are also functionally identical to save states.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Game designers often attempt to integrate the save points into the style of the game using skeuomorphism.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Although save points are typically seen as boons, some games have traps which use this tendency to fool the player.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In *Chrono Trigger*, attempting to use a fake save point in Magus's castle can actually bring the party into battle.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some games employ limits to saving in order to prevent players from using them as a primary means of succeeding in the game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In the console versions of *Tomb Raider (1996)* & *Tomb Raider III* save points are consumed upon use, *Donkey Kong Country 2: Diddy's Kong Quest* charges two banana coins to use a save point more than once, and in *Resident Evil* the player must find and expend an ink ribbon for each save.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In some games, save games or save points are part of the plot.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In *Chrono Cross*, save points are called Records of Fate, managed by an entity called FATE, an antagonist that uses the save points to control people.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In *Anonymous;Code*, the protagonist Pollon Takaoka has a unique ability to save and load save games, which is central to the plot and the main game mechanic.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Another way saved games interact with each other is through passing along data to sequels.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] A famous example of this is the first three installments of the *Wizardry* series.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] To play the second and third installments, players needed to import the characters they'd used in the previous installment, which retained all experience and equipment gained in that installment.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Later versions of the games made this feature optional, as do franchises such as the *Fire Emblem*, *Shenmue* and *.hack* series.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Video games may also take the saved games of other video games into account; for example, the character Rosalina becomes available on *Mario Kart Wii* if there is a *Super Mario Galaxy* save on the console.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] The save game of *Midnight Club 3: DUB Edition* can be imported to the Remix version of the game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] For many years, sharing game saves among friends has been very common.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] From trading passwords to swapping memory cards, gamers have always been able to help each other out to unlock features in a game.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] With the growing popularity of the Internet, many people upload their game saves to help out their online friends.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] However, with the inclusion of a progress meter or "gamerscore" that tracks player progress in games for the Xbox 360, many players are beginning to view those who load other people's files onto their systems as "cheaters".
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] Some games such as *Grand Theft Auto IV* attempt to prevent the use of saved games made by other users.
[src:save-game-serialization/saved-game] In contrast, *The Legend of Zelda: Oracle of Seasons and Oracle of Ages* actively encourages players that have completed the game to share their progress with others via a password swapping side quest that is available after finishing the main story.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
