[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:save-game-serialization/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
